When you have two direction vectors,
the Cross Product gives you a third vector that is perpendicular (at 90Â°) to both.
-->Vector3 cross = Vector3.Cross(A, B);
Vector3.Cross(Vector3.forward, Vector3.right) = Vector3.up;
Vector3.Cross(Vector3.right, Vector3.forward) = Vector3.down;


| Concept               | Meaning                                   | Unity Example                        |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| `Vector3.Cross(A, B)` | Vector perpendicular to A & B             | `Vector3.Cross(forward, right) = up` |
| **Right-Hand Rule**   | Direction of result                       | Thumb of right hand                  |
| **Order matters**     | Cross(A, B) = â€“Cross(B, A)                | Flips direction                      |
| **Use Cases**         | Find up/right, surface normals, rotations | Lighting, AI, camera, terrain        |
| **Always 90Â°**        | Result always perpendicular               | Orthogonal basis vectors             |
